Communicate Data Finding¶

Ford GoBike System Data

by Rinad Bankher¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Ford GoBike is a regional public bicycle sharing system located in San Francisco Bay Area. This dataset shows history data of individual rides made in a bike-sharing system at 2019.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The original dataset contains 183412 rides and 16 features. I added three additional features by feature engineering.

  1. duration_sec: the trip duration in seconed
  2. start_time: the trip start time with date
  3. end_time: the trip end time with date
  4. start_station_id: start station id
  5. start_station_name: start station name
  6. start_station_latitude: start station latitude
  7. start_station_longitude: start station longitude
  8. end_station_id: end station id
  9. end_station_name: end station name
  10. end_station_latitude: end station latitude
  11. end_station_longitude: end station longitude
  12. bike_id: rented bike id
  13. user_type: user type either Subscriber or Customer
  14. member_birth_year: member year of birth
  15. member_gender: member gender

  16. bike_share_for_all_trip : True if the member enrolled in the "Bike Share for All" program for low-income residents Additional features

  17. member_age: age of user

  18. hours: time of ride
  19. weekdays: day of ride

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • Age
  • Gender
  • Membership Status
  • Weekday
  • Hour

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  1. user_type
  2. member_gender
  3. member_age
  4. hours
  5. weekdays

Issue 2: Wrong datatype for start_time,user_type,member_gender and member_birth_year columns¶

Define¶

Change user_type and member_gender columns to category using astype method. Change column member_birth_year to int. Change column start_time to datetime format.

Code¶

In [10]:
bike_rent_clean.user_type = bike_rent_clean.user_type.astype('category')
bike_rent_clean.member_gender = bike_rent_clean.member_gender.astype('category')
bike_rent_clean.member_birth_year = bike_rent_clean.member_birth_year.astype(int)
bike_rent_clean.start_time = pd.to_datetime(bike_rent_clean.start_time)

The box plot and 95% percentile using describe pandas function show older users above 55 years old to be outliers. So, I chose to drop rows above 60 years old.

Univariate Exploration¶

Q1. What is the distribution of Ford GoBike users age?¶

In [27]:
# Create histogram
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'member_age');

# Set plot labels and title
plt.title('Ford GoBike Users Age Distribution\n')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Number of Users');

The distribution is right-skewed, with the Majority of users from 28 to 33 years old use the GoBike system.

Q2. What is the proportion of each user gender?¶

In [28]:
# Get the dynamic ordering of genders
sorted_counts = df['member_gender'].value_counts()

# Create pie plot
plt.pie(sorted_counts, labels = sorted_counts.index, startangle = 90,autopct= '%1.1f%%', counterclock = False);
plt.axis('square');
plt.title('Ford GoBike Users Proportion by Gender\n\n');

The male users are more than half with 74.4%, while 23.5% goes for female users and 2.1% for other gender.

Q3. What is the proportion of each user type?¶

# Get the dynamic ordering of user types

fig = plt.figure(figsize = [15,10])

# plot heatmap for customer users
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
# Get the number of customer users for each hour and weekday as a pandas series
c_type = df.query('user_type == "Customer"').groupby(["hours", "weekdays"]).size()
# Convert a series into a dataframe object
c_type = c_type.reset_index(name='count')
# Rearrange the data, to have hours on rows
c_type = c_type.pivot(index = 'hours', columns = 'weekdays', values = 'count')
# Plot heatmap with color templete
sb.heatmap(c_type, cmap='YlGnBu')

# Set plot title and axis labels 
plt.title('Customer', y=1.01)
plt.xlabel('Weekdays')
plt.ylabel('Hours');


# plot heatmap for subscriber users

# Convert a series into a dataframe object
s_type = s_type.reset_index(name='count')
# Rearrange the data, to have hours on rows
s_type = s_type.pivot(index = 'hours', columns = 'weekdays', values = 'count')
